# Extension CHANGELOG.md Rules

## Purpose

Every Isaac Sim extension has a `docs/CHANGELOG.md` that records notable changes per
version. It is a quick-scan history for users and maintainers, not a narrative or a
substitute for the git log.

## Keep It Concise

Changelogs MUST be kept concise. Brevity is the priority.

- An entry can be multiple sentences or span multiple lines when needed — just keep it
  concise. Say what changed and why it matters, then stop.
- Lead with the affected symbol/file when relevant (e.g., `` `ClassName.method`: ... ``),
  then the change.
- Omit empty sections. Only include headers that have entries.
- Do NOT include: implementation walkthroughs, reasoning paragraphs, migration tutorials,
  code blocks, screenshots, or restated diffs. Link or point to docs instead.
- Do NOT duplicate Overview.md content or full API reference details.
- Do NOT include task, bug, or issue tracker IDs. Describe the user-visible change instead;
  internal references stay in the commit/MR, not the changelog.
- Prefer the smallest set of entries that accurately captures user-visible impact. Collapse
  many tiny internal tweaks into a single representative entry rather than listing each one.

## Format

Follow the [Keep a Changelog 1.1.0](https://keepachangelog.com/en/1.1.0/) format.

- `# Changelog` heading at the top of the file.
- Changelogs are for humans, not machines — write notable changes, not a git log dump.
- Newest version first (reverse chronological), using `## [X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD` with
  ISO 8601 (`YYYY-MM-DD`) dates.
- The version MUST match `version` in `config/extension.toml`, and versions should adhere to
  [Semantic Versioning](https://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html).
- Group entries under the standard Keep a Changelog headers, in this order when present:
  `### Added`, `### Changed`, `### Deprecated`, `### Removed`, `### Fixed`, `### Security`.
  - `Added` for new features.
  - `Changed` for changes in existing functionality.
  - `Deprecated` for soon-to-be removed features.
  - `Removed` for now removed features.
  - `Fixed` for bug fixes.
  - `Security` for vulnerability fixes.
- Group the same types of changes together; always list deprecations, removals, and breaking
  changes so upgrades are predictable.
- Use present/past tense consistently with existing entries; write in imperative or
  descriptive mood ("Add ...", "Fix ...", or "Added ...", "Fixed ...").

## Example

```markdown
# Changelog

## [0.2.1] - 2026-04-27
### Fixed
- `MobilityGenRobot.get_pose_2d`: fix `NameError` for missing `np` import.

### Changed
- Replay runs with multi-GPU rendering disabled.
```
